SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 1237
By Walley
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Kermit Taze Lofton, Sr.,
of Henderson.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Kermit Taze Lofton, Sr.; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Lofton was a highly respected member of his community and a
consummate professional who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow
citizens in numerous capacities; and
WHEREAS, born in Adamsville on May 9, 1940, Taze Lofton was the son of Taze Elmo
Lofton and Verda Lee Whitten Lofton; he moved with his family to Millington and attended
Millington High School, where he was a member of the marching band, before moving once
more with his family to Henderson, graduating from Chester County High School in 1958; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Lofton attended Freed-Hardeman College for one year, where he was a
member of the Griffin's Men's Tumbling Team, and transferred to Bethel College in 1961,
graduating in 1964 with a degree in business administration; and
WHEREAS, while attending Bethel College, he met the love of his life, Nancy Karen
Barnerd; the two were wed on July 11, 1964, and made their home in Henderson; and
WHEREAS, after graduating from college, he worked for Casey Funeral Home and at
Goodyear as a credit sales manager, while also farming on the family land; he then went into
business with Anthony Bolton and opened Bolton-Lofton Used Cars; and
WHEREAS, in 1972, Taze Lofton and Anthony Bolton purchased Stroud Chevrolet in
Henderson, renaming the franchise Bolton-Lofton Chevrolet; in 1978, Mr. Lofton became
primary owner of the dealership, and the name was changed to Lofton Chevrolet, Inc.; and
SJR1237
018419
- 1 -

WHEREAS, he retired from the dealership in 2008, leaving the business with his sons
and General Manager Ronnie Geary; in 2022, Mr. Lofton and the Lofton Chevrolet Family
celebrated 50 years of business, during which time they had been blessed with numerous
wonderful loyal employees and customers; and
WHEREAS, after retiring, Mr. Lofton returned to his love for farmland and working
outdoors and became interested in heavy equipment; he could often be seen on his backhoe or
trackhoe moving dirt and cleaning his farm in Pinson in south Madison County; and
WHEREAS, an avid race car driver, Taze Lofton competed on various dirt tracks in West
Tennessee, driving a black B-car sporting the number 62; a crowd favorite, he went two full
seasons without a loss in a feature race and held the track record at various speedways,
including Riverside Speedway in West Memphis, Arkansas; and
WHEREAS, he had a lifetime love of cars and racing and was a collector of antique cars,
especially the 1963-1967 Corvette; he was also a passionate NASCAR fan, traveling to
numerous tracks across the country to cheer on his favorite man in black, Dale Earnhardt. He
and his wife enjoyed international traveling with the GM cooperation, and RV camping with their
fellow NASCAR friend traveling crew; and
WHEREAS, his other avocations included golfing as a member of the Woodland Hills
Golf and Country Club, boating, and spending time with his family at his home at Pine Lake; and
WHEREAS, Taze Lofton served his community as a member of Henderson Church of
Christ, as well as a volunteer at Freed-Hardeman University and a member of the University's
Development Council and President's Council; he was honored to receive the University's
Volunteer of the Year Award for 2006-2007; and
WHEREAS, Taze Lofton was also deeply devoted to his family and always endeavored
to remain true to family values of the highest order; and
- 2 - 018419

WHEREAS, he will be sadly missed but fondly remembered by his wife of sixty-one
years, Nancy; sons, Kermit (Debbie) Lofton and Spence (Julia) Lofton; grandchildren, Drew
Lofton, Alex Lofton, Spencer Lofton, and Paige Lofton; and sister, Nona Lofton (Dwain) Seaton;
and
WHEREAS, in addition to his parents, Mr. Lofton was preceded in death by his brothers,
Larry Lofton and Leon Lofton, as well as a nephew, Leon Lofton, Jr.; and
WHEREAS, Taze Lofton leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should pause to remember the bountiful life of this
exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Kermit Taze Lofton, Sr.,
reflecting fondly upon his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the
examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Lofton.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
